MER Hardship Waiver Data Analysis

2025-04-01

Introduction This report analyzes Medicaid estate recovery trends in four states using FY 2019 data. It focuses on the relationship between recovery rates, hardship waiver policies, and socioeconomic factors.

Page 20, Medicaid estate recovery intensity across four states in FY 2019

#Figure 1
ggplot(MER_Data, aes(x = reorder(State, `Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`), 
                 y = `Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`)) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = reorder(State, `Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`),
                   yend = 0), color = "gray70", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 5, color = "#2C77B2") +
  geom_text(aes(label = percent(`Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending` / 100, accuracy = 0.01)), 
            hjust = -0.4, size = 4) +
  coord_flip(clip = "off") +
  expand_limits(y = max(MER_Data$`Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`) + 0.2) +
  labs(
    title = "Estate Recovery as % of LTSS Spending (FY 2019)",
    subtitle = "Higher values indicate more aggressive estate recovery policies",
    x = "",
    y = "Estate Recovery (% of LTSS Spending)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 13, color = "gray30"),
    axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    plot.margin = margin(10, 30, 10, 10)
  )

Page 21, The inverse relationship between state poverty rates and the share of LTSS spending recovered through Estate Recovery.

#Figure 2
ggplot(MER_Data, aes(x = `Poverty Rate 65+ (%)`, y = `Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`, label = State)) +
  geom_point(size = 5, color = "#2C77B2") +
  geom_text(nudge_y = 0.4, size = 4.2, check_overlap = TRUE) +  # label offset above the point
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "firebrick", linewidth = 1.2) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(scale = 1, accuracy = 0.1)) +
  labs(
    title = "Estate Recovery vs. Poverty Rate 2019",
    subtitle = "States with higher poverty tend to recover less LTSS spending",
    x = "Poverty Rate",
    y = "Estate Recovery (% of LTSS Spending)"
  ) +
  coord_cartesian(clip = "off") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 13, color = "gray30"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10)),
    axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(r = 10)),
    plot.margin = margin(10, 30, 10, 30)
  )

Page 24, Hardship Waiver Policy Components by State

#Figure 5
waiver_long <- MER_Data %>%
  select(State, 
         B_Accessibility, 
         C_Clarity, 
         D_ModeOfComm, 
         E_PublicEdEfforts, 
         F_ScopeOfWaiver, 
         G_LegalAdminBurden) %>%
  pivot_longer(-State, names_to = "Component", values_to = "Score")


waiver_long$Component <- recode(waiver_long$Component,
  B_Accessibility = "Accessibility (15)",
  C_Clarity = "Clarity (15)",
  D_ModeOfComm = "Communication (15)",
  E_PublicEdEfforts = "Public Education (01)",
  F_ScopeOfWaiver = "Waiver Scope (15)",
  G_LegalAdminBurden = "Legal Burden (15)"
)


p <- ggplot(waiver_long, aes(x = Score, y = reorder(State, Score), color = Component)) +
  geom_point(size = 4, alpha = 0.9) +
  facet_wrap(~Component, scales = "free_x", ncol = 3) +
  labs(
    title = "Hardship Waiver Policy Components by State",
    x = "Component Score",
    y = ""
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(margin = margin(b = 10)),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12),
    legend.position = "none"
  )

p

#Figure 6
ggplot(MER_Data, aes(x = B_Accessibility, 
                     y = `Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`,
                     fill = as.factor(C_Clarity),
                     label = State)) +
  geom_point(shape = 21, size = 6, color = "black", stroke = 0.6) +
  geom_text_repel(size = 4.2, point.padding = 0.3, min.segment.length = 0) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("1" = "#A6CEE3", "2" = "#1F78B4"),
    name = "Clarity",
    labels = c("1 = Low", "2 = High")
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 3:5, limits = c(2.5, 5.2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(scale = 1, accuracy = 0.1),
                     limits = c(0, 1.9)) +
  labs(
    title = "Estate Recovery vs. Accessibility of Waiver Policy",
    subtitle = "Point color indicates clarity level (1 = Low, 2 = High)",
    x = "Accessibility Score (15)",
    y = "Estate Recovery (% of LTSS Spending)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 13, color = "gray30"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10)),
    axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(r = 10)),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.box = "horizontal",
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 11)
  )

# Figure 7
fig7 <- ggplot(MER_Data, aes(
  x = Waiver_Protectiveness_Score,
  y = `Estate Recovery % of LTSS Spending`,
  color = `Poverty Rate 65+ (%)`
)) +
  geom_point(size = 6) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = State), size = 4.5, color = "black") +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#C6DBEF", high = "#08306B", name = "Poverty Rate (%)") +

  labs(
    title = "Estate Recovery vs. Waiver Protectiveness Score",
    subtitle = "Point color shows poverty rate (age 65+) for each state",
